restaurant.name: Taco Mamacita
restaurant.timings: 11 AM to 10 PM (Mon, Tue, Wed, Thu, Sun), 11 AM to 11 PM (Fri-Sat)

photo.caption: Enchiladas Suiza and Jalapeño Corn Slaw

review.review_text: This place is just ok for Mexican food. It is very commercial and non authentic. While I would not go back for the food, I would go for drinks. This place does have a festive vibe you can enjoy celebrating with friends and family.

The atmosphere and location are nice but the food has always been a little middle of the road for me. Service is generally a little slow but the margaritas are usually really good. I go if someone else suggests but its never on my list of places I'd pick. Not terrible, not great.
DELICIOUS!!!! Best taco place ever! Very friendly service. They have a lot of vegan and vegetarian options which made me very happy! Really great prices too!

Atmosphere: college and thirty something crowd, mostly locals. Decor: typical Mexican flare with a fun, eclectic, Nashville twist. Service:  as always, fantastic and attentive. Drinks:  very well crafted, correct amounts of liquor. Food: great choices, well prepared. HIGHLY RECOMMEND!!!

Very good experience. Food was delivered quickly and was hot. I had the Sloppy Jose Taco and the Buffalo Chicken special, both of which were excellent. A must-visit if you are in Nashville. Couldn’t recommend more.

review.review_text: The food and atmosphere was fantastic southern. The food is great. The staff is friendly. I had southwest omelette and bisquitte and gravy. All excellent. The price was reasonable no complaints.

Went for lunch 9/9/18 we got fried chicken fried catfish chicken gizzards with turnip greens fried green tomatoes fried okra white beans geeen beans Mac and cheese and fudge pie was all wonderful food and the service was impeccable

When I came here I was expecting a touristy spot, especially since they have a whole Loveless subculture with stores & all sorts of branded stuff nearby. However, I found it honestly good southern food. The meats there were great and the drinks were excellent too. The service was extremely good as well. I got to see why they are such a famous place - there's really nothing you can blame here. They seem to have it figured out

Where to Eat Instead Of Loveless Cafe  feast.media/where-to-eat-instead-of-loveless-cafe Loveless Cafe has been a staple of the Nashville community and what I like to call the world wide community of soul food lovers, or the WWCOFS for short. Many people know this genre of food as soul food, meat and three, southern, or even comfort food. As a native of Nashville, I have been coming to Loveless since before I was born. For a while all the hype was true, Loveless was the best place to go if you want real southern food. However, more than just management changed years ago, and it hasn't been able to restore the former quality that everyone from this town remembers. Now Loveless is busier than they ever have been and the food isn't even half as good.   Now, this next piece of information isn't something to go spreading around to everyone you know visiting or living in Nashville. The reason this place is special is because there aren't herds of people being bussed in to wait 45 minutes in line for cheese grits slathered in a stack of Kraft American singles to the point you feel like you're drinking processed cheese whiz with a sprinkle of grits. You won't feel like you are inside a chain restaurant owned by Opryland. There isn't anyone trying to sell you merchandise while you are cooped up in the waiting area trying to decide whether or not you want to wait any longer for this food.   Where you want to go instead of Loveless is a magical place on Old Hillsboro road right outside of the Nashville city limits that goes by the name Barbara's Home Cooking. If you have been to Loveless and you first arrive at Barbaras, you will be wondering where the line is? Well, I have literally never seen a line there and they have open seating. Once you walk into this home turned restaurant, the lovely women who run the place will greet you with authentic South African accents and the warmest, densest, fluffiest, roll that has ever melted in your mouth. The menu is written on a chalkboard on the wall and almost never changes. The benefit to not having tons of options is that they are able to make everything as fresh as possible.

I went into my meal at Loveless thinking "This must be an overhyped tourist spot". Boy, was I wrong. It's honest and delicious southern comfort food. I went with my family, so we did the family style meal. For our meats, we got fried chicken and pulled pork. Both were great, but the fried chicken was probably the best I've ever had. It's done right. I wouldn't go there for the pulled pork, but it was still better than I expected. For our sides, we got macaroni and cheese, mashed potatoes and gravy, and hash brown casserole. The macaroni and mashed potatoes were superb. However, I didn't find myself drawn to the hashbrown casserole as much. It was great, but not the best I've had.  Overall, I'd give Loveless an A+. The staff is friendly and warm. There's always a long wait, but there's a reason for that- Everyone wants to eat there. It's one of the best food experiences I've had around the Franklin area. 10/10 recommend.
